        "title": "Death dissolves jurisdiction — released from the Law to be joined to Christ",
        "range": "7:1-6",
        "excerpt": "Therefore, my brethren, you also were made to die to the Law through the body of Christ, so that you might be joined to another, to Him who was raised from the dead, in order that we might bear fruit for God.",
        "body": "Paul has just finished chapter 6 with the believer's death-with-Christ to sin. Chapter 7 opens with the corresponding death-to-the-Law, and the question of how that death is legally effected. The principle Paul lays down in v. 1 is one any reader of Torah would accept: *the Law has jurisdiction over a person as long as he lives*. The Law's claim is durational — it operates on a living subject and ends at death.\n\nThe widow illustration (vv. 2-3) presses the point with one specific application. While her husband lives, the marriage law binds her to him; if she takes another man, she is an *adulteress* (*moichalis*). But if her husband dies, the same law releases her — she is *free from the law concerning the husband* and may marry another without becoming an adulteress. The mechanism Paul highlights is *the death*, not divorce or repudiation. Death is what ends jurisdiction.\n\nThe application in v. 4 is where readers have often stumbled. Strictly, in the analogy, it is *the husband* (the Law) who should die, freeing the wife (the believer). But Paul reverses it: *you also were made to die to the Law*. The point is not allegorical correspondence but legal mechanism — *somebody* must die for jurisdiction to end, and Paul says it is the believer who died, in Christ's death (*through the body of Christ*). The body of Christ on the cross is the legal instrument of release. And the purpose is positive, not merely negative: not just freed *from* the old husband but joined *to another* — *Him who was raised from the dead*. Released to be remarried. The fruit of the new union is *fruit for God* (v. 4), whereas the old union produced *fruit for death* (v. 5).\n\nVerse 6 closes with the chapter's first *nuni de* — *but now*. Paul announces the eschatological 'now' of the new covenant: *we serve in newness of the Spirit and not in oldness of the letter*. This is the seed of chapter 8. The believer is not lawless; the believer serves — but the mode is *the Spirit*, not *the letter* (cf. 2 Corinthians 3:6). The Law as external code is rendered inoperative (*katargeō*) as the regulator of the believer's life; the Spirit as internal indweller takes that role.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Katargeō* (vv. 2, 6) is Paul's strong term for *rendering inoperative* — used 27 times in his letters, often of cosmic powers nullified by the cross. *Karpophoreō* (vv. 4, 5) is agricultural — bearing fruit as the outcome of a union. *Nuni de* (v. 6) is Paul's signature 'but now' announcing the new state of affairs (cf. 3:21; 6:22). *Gramma* (letter, v. 6) versus *pneuma* (Spirit) anticipates 2 Corinthians 3:6 and is one of Paul's structural contrasts between old covenant and new."
